comment: There’s something so special about this community here. Everyone is so kind and positive. Only if all the other channels were like this. I look forward to this 30 day every year for the wonderful practices, but the community is another reason I do. So proud of you all and so honored to do yoga like this with everyone from around the world. Thank you for bringing us all together Adriene!

I feel like I do have to agree with a lot of comments. This practice was hard. I managed pretty well (some child's poses instead of down dogs and), but while I am not the most experienced participant here, generally hard practices were shorter and I felt that that was a great motivator to do it anyway. I still have some hidden core strength from my roller derby days which is what made this managable, but I can't say I feel very "zen" so I can imagine how it feels for the people who struggled more. Maybe something to think about for next year! I did part of Breath last year and I do find the progression of Move quite steep in comparison. Caught myself thinking "I'm glad I know these poses and transitions already", especially today.
Lots of sweat
Good morning Adriene! I am ready to explore my strength today! Thank you for whatever todays practice will bring. I appreciate you. Have a wonderful weekend!, 🙏🏽💪🏽🎉🧘🏽‍♀️
Namaste! We are strong! Thank you, Adriene!
Thank you Adriene but man this was hard!  I keep having spasms in my feet and today they were quite active!

I felt like this one went from level 1 yoga to level 10. When asked how I was feeling when we turned over to lie on our backs, it was frustrated and angry. My arms could not hold me up for all those plank poses. Up until today I felt pretty good after practice. I had been noticing that I'd been getting stronger. But, today was too much. I'm now starting my day trying to shake this frustration.

Day 27 ✅ This one was hard for me and felt the pressure in my wrists. I had difficulty keeping up too and it is the first time where I had to pause the video to keep up! I guess I need to work on my core more. I also noticed that Adriene loves more asanas on the hands than on the feet. 😄😄Anyway I pushed through it and felt good to have a cardio workout!    Thanks Adriene and Benji! 💕💜💙💚
I'm only 17 and I have been consistent with this practice so proud😭I cant do yoga with you Adrienne ❤
This flow whipped my butt! I love how short and impactful this flow is. Saved for future after-work workouts, thank you 💜💜

The written invitation for this STRONG practice reached a tender spot; as i read about "the hope molecule "it brought a tear and a smile, having recently fought breast cancer. You have honestly had my back, as I started through recovery. I kinda of feel like we're soul sisters!

I’ve been practicing yoga ever since the True series and I always recommend a 30 day journey to anyone who wants to start yoga. This year I got my partner to join me on Move. It has been our little January ritual to do yoga in the living room together, it’s been so much fun! We really noticed our bodies and minds getting stronger because of our regular practice. Unfortunately we both caught covid the last week of January. I’ve only just got back to my mat and this practice asked a lot of me. Thank you Adriene for reminding me that what I most need is forgiveness and not *getting back into shape asap*. I will spend my final days of Move practice making sure my movement aligns with my new breathing pattern and being forgiving to myself for getting behind on the challenge. I am strong! :)
Adriene thank you with all of my heart, you are amazing! 💜🙏☺️

This is for all levels of ability and if you persevere that level comes up. She IS always reminding us not to kill ourselves in the process, accept failure as part of the learning process. In my seventies, I realise my ability may go down, but I’ll still do what I can, but YWA has seen me through so many crises.

When I first did this practice, I STRUGGLED. I felt really discouraged. I did not do well, but I knew I could do it. Today, I revisited this practice and am proud to say I followed along successfully and never gave up. I knew that I was capable and strong enough to do this physically but for some reason when I had first tried this session I was not in a good place mentally. Its incredible how strong (or weak) our minds can make us feel... When really we are more than capable. Never give up on yourself!

At the hardest point I started to cry... Because of my fight, my struggle, my nevergiveup willpower, than I realized everything what have gone with tears was stress deep inside me. So this session was a huge relief for my soul.. I can't be more grateful to find you, Adriene, you are a lifesaver truly.

14:49-14:54 It would have been great if this modification had been introduced as an option in the beginning of the sequence. About four days ago the scoliosis in my lumbar spine started really acting up. I got some constant pain that I’ve never had there for this long. And it’s been sticking with me. At this point I’m only assuming it’s my scoliosis, it could be a muscle strain or something more severe. But for now I’m gonna call it my scoliosis.

This has made the last few days of yoga really challenging and in turn it’s triggered a flare up of my fibromyalgia and cfs. So I’m exhausted and in tons of pain in my whole body now. Yesterday I really pushed myself too far in yoga even though I thought I was being careful, I ended up so sore I felt like crying.

So today, through this strong practice, I adapted the whole time. I lifted my legs and touched my knees to my elbows while in table with a pillow under my knees. Taking breaks as I needed to. I took a couple down dogs, but mostly adapted with puppy posture and a pillow under my knees. I took every movement slowly and stoped if I felt any sharp pains. I focused on my breath and I definitely still got sweaty.

But lemme tell you, my back is thanking me for adapting today. Maybe next month I’ll be able to do this one, maybe not. But I’m proud of myself for intentionally adapting and inviting softness and compassion into this practice. I hope this encourages any of you who’ve been struggling with these practices due to injury or fatigue or sickness or mental health.

You got this, take what you need, leave what you don’t.

Adapting through the whole practice can bring you beautiful things. It doesn’t lessen, it deepens. It brings you closer to yourself and it’s a loving gesture that your body and mind will thank you for 💜

Wow, that was intense.  I am strong.  I had a hysterectomy 5 years ago this past Wednesday.  I had been so sick with abnormal uterine bleeding for a year.  In one weekend I lost so much blood that I almost needed a transfusion.  My body was so weak, and I did not have core muscles.  I started practicing yoga last March, and this year my goal is to practice every day.  This 30 day journey is one I do not want to end.  I used to not be able to do planks, push ups, sit ups, etc.  I can do these things now.  I am strong, strong body and strong mind.  Thank you, Adriene, and the rest of this beautiful community for inspiring me every day. Namaste 💛

Today really brought me to edge, and then over! 15 min in I completely broke down, paused the video and just started sobbing in child's pose. After years, on and off, of YWA as well as this being my 57th day of yoga in a row, I still seriously struggled. When Adriene said "Whisper to yourself, I am strong" I just yelled "F*** you!" not very yogi of me ahaha, but it was a very real reaction in that moment, feeling seriously challenged and weak, doubting myself and all I've worked towards these past couple months. Coming through that anger and those tears though, getting back on the mat and doing what I could in that moment showed me that I truly am a lot stronger than I thought. It may not be the physical strength that I thought I wanted but instead having the ability to show up exactly as I am, yell and cry, feel the anger, pain, and sadness but then come back. Today I may not have nailed the poses or even have come close but I didn't give up on myself and that is my strength.

Thank you Adriene for challenging me in a way that showed me my true strength. 
Thank you to this community for showing me that I am enough and that I'm not alone in this.

Wow. I am so humbled by this journey. I've been practicing for over 15 years and every year Adriene's 30 days teaches me something new. 

But this year... something is different. It's so powerful, so intense, so deep and so heartfelt. I am again, so utterly humbled and today's practice was the icing on the cake. Not because I could lean in and push through but because I could FEEL it so DEEP. The intention, the willpower and the extreme love I feel when I move (and yes, muscles too 😅) and after I have moved.

This is not just a yoga journey. It's an inner journey of (re-)learning our inner strength and stamina. While we're moving we're also conditioning our mind to take the practice off the mat. Moving is hard but so is showing up as a human being in all situations. And I can truly say that I am becoming a much better person this January. I've gained strength, stamina, courage, grace, a sense of ease, kindness (to myself and others), acceptance... the list goes on and on. 

I wish there was a more powerful way to say "thank you" but I think you know what I mean, and I think I speak for most of us, when I say that our gratitude is beyond. From my heart to yours, Adriene, wow! ❤️🙏🏻

Adriene I am beyond greatful for these journeys and practices you provide for us! If I could offer some feedback: 1. today's session was FIRE! so tough and challenging. Maybe I am alone in this, but I would love if this session was preceded by a leg-dominant session. the last few days left my shoulders SORE and it was a bit disheartening to not be able to complete all the poses and flows. Maybe having this specific practice after a leg-dominant or rest day would be less tiring.
2. mountain climbers and 3-legged dog to mountain climber uses a surprising amount of inner thigh! I noticed this journey is a little more geared towards the upper body (and I love! that), so I was very surprised by the inner thigh muscles activating. I would personally love some more poses isolating the inner thighs sprinkled into the practices.

Again, this is all just feedback I give with love and support - sharing my personal experience in hopes it can resonate with some, and perhaps even improvements for the next year! I love these 30 day journeys and will continue to recommend and participate regardless. Much love to this community!
